tidied_drivers: fishing (clams, worms); turbidity; precipitation; wind speed; temperature

all_species: thalassia testudinum, halodule wrightii, syringodium filiforme, ruppia maritima, halophila engelmannii
notes: Use late fall/early winter aerial photos; Have all of Tampa Bay split into multiple areas
other drivers considered: positive feedbacks of increased seagrass populations recovering; decreased pH

title: Multiple stressors threaten the imperiled coastal foundation species eelgrass (Zostera marina) in Chesapeake Bay, USA
notes: NA
primary driver: water clarity, salinity, total nitogren, total phosphorous, temperature, maximum temperature
statistical analysis: general additive model: density weighted cover ~ long,lat + cover + habitat + salinity + secchi + total nitrogen + total phosphorous + temperature + maxt temperature + secchi * temp
tidied_drivers: turbidity; salinity; nutrients; nitrogen; phosphorous; temperature

title: Multi-temporal change detection of seagrass beds using integrated Landsat TM/ETM +/OLI imageries in Cam Ranh Bay, Vietnam
all_species: enhalus acoroides, halophila ovalis, halophila minor, thalassia hemprichii, halodule pinifolia, halodule uninervis, ruppia maritima
notes: primary goal of study was to detect changes in seagrass cover using landsat data - attribution was not goal of this study
statistical analysis: - verbal comparisons with - visual comparison of images showing seagrass beds were replaced by aquaculture farms: “The mapping results in 2015 (Fig. 6f) not only had a high overall accuracy of 91.68%, but also had close agreement with Google imagery in 2014 (Fig. 8b), showing that all lost seagrass areas were occupied by aquaculture farms.”

title: The impact of 85 years of coastal development on shallow seagrass beds (Posidonia oceanica L. (Delile)) in South Eastern France: A slow but steady loss without recovery
notes: They also calculated distance of impacts - The impact magnitude of all different types of coastline settlements. Principal causes of seagrass loss were harbours (83.8%) and artificial beaches (10.3%). principal causes were harbours (83.8%) and artificial beaches (10.3%). principal causes were harbours (83.8%) and artificial beaches (10.3%). Highest reclamation area from the sea was observed between 1920 (1643.19ha) and 2010 (3945.56ha); (harbours, ports of refuge, landfills, artificial beaches, groynes and pontoons) that caused losses (level 1 of certainty) were analyzed. The area (in m2;) of every settlement of each type was calculated and the total (direct þ indirect) area of meadow loss was estimated within a 200 m, 500 m, 1000 m, 2000 m, 5000 m and 10 000 m radius from them.
primary driver: land reclamation - artifical coastline construction (harbours, ports of refuge, landfills, artifical beaches, groynes and pontoons), submarine pipelines, aquatic farms
statistical analysis: visual comparison of aerial photographs; before after comparisons
tidied_drivers: coastal development (land reclamation, coastal armouring, subtidal pipelines); aquaculture

title: Application of Landsat images to seagrass areal cover change analysis for Lawas, Terengganu and Kelantan of Malaysia
all_species: halodule pinifolia, thalassia hemprichii, halophila minor, halophila ovalis, cymodocea rotundata
notes:
Specific objectives of this study were to: (1) estimate identifiable changes in the seagrasses and coastal land cover areas with differing landscape structure, and coastlines, using radio- metric enhancement integrated with seed pixel growing algorithm on multi-date Landsat images for the intertidal and subtidal sea- grass meadows of Lawas, and lagoons of Terengganu and Kelantan, and (2) identify and discuss possible links between seagrass cover changes and natural and anthropogenic drivers. No real evidence behind attributions.
Data extracted for aerial cover from Figure 5.
statistical analysis: descriptive, visual -field observations and image comparison; land use and cover analysis, image comparisons

title: Observation of typhoon-induced seagrass die-off using remote sensing
all_species: zostera marina, zostera caulescens, halophila nipponica
notes: Area km2 extracted from figure 5. This study aimed to identify the pattern of long-term change in the area of seagrass beds using historical satellite images, and to elucidate the causes for the seagrass die-off in whole of the bay in 2012 - found that A die-off of seagrass beds was observed in September 2012 after Typhoon Bolaven, Tembin, and Sanba consecutively passed the study site. When Typhoon Sanba passed the study site, it had sustained maximum wind speed (147.6 km h 1) during low tide, unlike the other typhoons. visual - compares area cover to the years that the typhoons came through. Descriptive - describes the effect of typhoon on seagrass beds in the area, relates to wind speed.

title: Widespread loss of the seagrass Syringodium isoetifolium after a major flood event in Moreton bay, Australia: Implications for benthic processes
all_species: zostera muelleri, syringodium isoetifolium, halophila ovalis, halodule uninervis, halophila spinulosa, cymodocea serrulata
notes: They also used aerial photography to look at the overall macroflora cover but this also included macroalage so I didn't include this data.
statistical analysis: visual - compares cover from survey/maps before and after flood event. Descriptive - measures salinity and light - compare before and after.

title: Ecosystem responses to long-term nutrient management in an urban estuary: Tampa Bay, Florida, USA
notes: Area data from table 1. Primarily looking at the invasion of s. isoetifolium into new meadows but still shows coverage changes between years. I have used the merged species data but they also have separate species data too. visual - compares area cover trends to trends in physical factors and major events. Descriptive - discusses in depth the result of the el nino event and associated physical variable measurements.
driver effect: positive (management); negative intially, followed by positive recovery (El nino)
statistical analysis: ANCOVA: rate of recovery before and after El Nino 1998; ANOVA: chlorophyll ~ nitrogen loading (indirect measure of water quality --> testing minimum light irradiance)

measurement method: literature review; Compiled published data in peer-review and grey literature reports until 2009 combined with own unpublished data.
title: Mediterranean seagrass (Posidonia oceanica) loss between 1842 and 2009
notes: Review paper of published/unpublished data without supplementary material. Provides a net loss value which I have included here. Also, has current max and min area value, which I average for our end area value. Intial extent is referenced in text.
primary driver: Industrial sewage, Aquaculture, Urban Seawage, invasions, coastal works, bottom trawling, anchoring, boating, turbidity/erosion, beach netting, thermic sewage, siltation
statistical analysis: descriptive, visual - graphs the causes identified in papers and shows number of meadows impacted by each pressure
tidied_drivers: nutrients; aquaculture; invasive species; fishing (beach netting); boating; turbidity; temperature

journal: PROCEEDINGS OF THE NATIONAL ACADEMY OF SCIENCES OF THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA
title: Recovery of a top predator mediates neagrive eutrophic effects on segrass
notes: Data extracted from Fig1A. Presence of otters allowed seagrass to expand rather then regress under high nutrient levels. Nutrient loading sstill has a negative effect but not as influenial.
statistical analysis: Linear regression: eelgrass expansion ~ otter predation on crabs (positive)
interaction of drivers considered: yes - visual plot of seagrass, niritate loads before and after sea otters
secondary driver statistical analysis: structural equation modelling: otters -> crabs -> mesograzers -> epiphytes -> producers, nutrients

notes: Data values are from figure 7 and are a total of cover area for all levels (Low, med, high). Some of the bars had error bars other didn't. measurement method: aerial photography, GPS field ground truthing, GIS
title: Hanging basket oyster farming: assessing effects on seagrass using aerial photography
notes: This is an experimental design with 1 impacted site and 5 controls. Area values from table 1. This site is the oyster farm "impacted site" All zones increased in seagrass area including the oyster farm zone. Although technically 'bounded' areas, the percent cover of seagrass in the bounded areas are so low that the bounded area is really just a measure of study extent/scale.
statistical analysis: BACI; Friedman repeated measures analysis of ranks: proportional change in seagrass area in controls and farmed area after farming.; Pearson’s chi-square goodness-of-fit test: percent cover of quadrats ~ position within oyster farm

notes: This is an experimental design with 1 impacted site and 5 controls. Area values from table 1. This site is the oyster farm "impacted site" All zones increased in seagrass area including the oyster farm zone. Although technically 'bounded' areas, the percent cover of seagrass in the bounded areas are so low that the bounded area is really just a measure of study extent/scale.
statistical analysis: BACI; Friedman repeated measures analysis of ranks: proportional change in seagrass area in controls and farmed area after farming.; Pearson’s chi-square goodness-of-fit test: percent cover of quadrats ~ position within oyster farm

tidied_drivers: nutrients; coastal development (dredging); management (water quality); precipitation; climate (El Nino)

title: Indigenous knowledge and long-term ecological change: detection, interpretation and responses to changing ecological conditions in Pacific Island communities
all_species: enhalus acoroides, thalassia hemprichii, halophila ovalis, cymodocea rotundata, cymodocea serrulata, halodule uninervis
notes: area cover values from figure 5. Study also looks at indigenous communities estimation on expansion/retraction seagrass based on local knowledge and observations. This type of data wasn't included in this data sheet.
primary driver: nutrient load, turbidity, extractivie logging activities - create more nutrients for growth. Sea level rise - faciliate shoreward mirgration of seagrass.
statistical analysis: descriptive - discusses some potential reasons for seagrass change in discussion
tidied_drivers: nutrients; turbidity; logging; sea level rise

primary driver: nutrients, light, pH (ruled out because so much successful oyster farming)
statistical analysis: visual - time series of environmental data
other drivers considered: oyster aquaculture, recreational hand fishing, freshwater
secondary driver attribution: descriptive - local threats discussion, no measurements made to this data

title: Dynamics of shallow-water assemblages in the Saipan Lagoon
notes: data from table 2 - added all habitat descriptions that mentioned seagrass expect sand with sparse seagrass as the paper didn't include that in their calculations. Halodule decreased by water flow velocity, increased by watershed development. Enhalus dependent on watershed size, positive relationship with human development.
driver effect: positive - watershed size, positive - watershed development, negative - water-flow velocity, positive - lagoon width
primary driver: watershed size, increased water flow velocity, watershed development
statistical analysis: multiple regression (area ~ watershed size + surface water-flow velocity + lagoon width)

title: Linking water quality to living resources in a mid-atlantic lagoon system, Usa
notes: Data figure 9 - it spilts the bars into different sites but it was going to be diificult to extract the data acturately so I have just gone for the overall Maryland bays data (all sites included). Sites included are: Assawoman Bay, Isle of Wight Bay, Sinepuxent Bay, Newport BAy, Chincoteague Bay. Seagrass shown to be increasing, but has levelled off over the last few years due to changing water quality conditions.
primary driver: water quality index (used threshold values for: chlorophyll a, total nitrogen, total phosphorous, dissolved oxygen)

title: Long term changes in Zostera meadows in the Berre Lagoon (Provence, Mediterranean Sea)
notes: Data from table 2 - probable surface area in hectares. There is also a min/max estimate value in the table. Despite the reduction in domestic and urban pollution, the beds still seem to be decreasing - but nitrogen concentrations didn't change nor did the seagrass cover.
primary driver: freshwater, silt and nutrient inputs causing light limitation - possibly from the Saint Chamas power plant start up
tidied_drivers: hydrology; light; nutrients; turbidity; coastal development (power plant)

title: Disturbance of eelgrass Zostera marina by commercial mussel Mytilus edulis harvesting in Maine: dragging impacts and habitat recovery
notes: values from table 1. Change analysis also availabile in table 1 (Dobson et al. 1995). Evidence of draggin apparent, in 2000 the total area showing evidence was 53.2ha (10% cover), however, overall, the decreases were lower than growth in the seagrass beds. Also includes a recovery projection.
driver effect: negative (but shows overall increase in total cover due to seagrass growth more then decline from dragging)
statistical analysis: t-tests: between disturbed and referenced sites (space for time)

measurement method: GIS mapping - Map-Info, approximate maximum depth limit polygon
title: Spatio-temporal dynamics of a Zostera noltii dominated community over a period of fluctuating salinity in a shallow lagoon, Southern France
notes: data extracted from figure 2. 1993, 1994, 1995 - surface area was estimated using the approximate maximum depth limit polygon
driver effect: no effect initially and then rapid decline (not associated with increase in freshwater species), followed by recovery after increase salinity
other drivers considered: light availability (from increase in suspended sediments), wave exposure
secondary driver statistical analysis: logistic regression: relative cover index ~ depth + relative exposure index + slope + percent fine sediment

notes: Values from table 2.
primary driver: shading by apiphytic algae following nitrogen enrichment, turbidity, scallop dredging, harbour construction, dredge spoil dumping, increased phytoplankton concentrations, overgrazing by sea urchins, direct removal by channel dredging, boat moorings, anchor drag, causeway construction

tidied_drivers: nutrients; light; epiphytic algae; turbidity; fishing (scallop dredging); coastal development (construction, dredging); boating (mooring, anchoring)

title: Benthic habitat mapping Owen Anchorage
dom_species: amphibolis antarctica, amphibolis griffithii, posidonia australis, posidonia sinuosa, posidonia coriacea
all_species: amphibolis antarctica, amphibolis griffithii, posidonia australis, posidonia sinuosa, posidonia coriacea, halophila ovalis, zostera tasmanica, syringodium isoetifolium
notes: Original Waycott paper was: Kendrick, GA, Benthic habitat mapping Owen Anchorage. 2004, Oceanica Consulting Pty Ltd and Cooperative Research Centre for Coastal Zone Estuaryand Waterways Management, Brisbane, Australia. Instead found: Kendrick et al. 2000. Changes in seagrass coverage in Cockburn Sound, Western Australia between 1965 and 1995. Estuarine, Coastal, and Shelf Science. Apparently H. ovalis, H. tasmanica, and S. isoetifolium not explicitly mapped, but they do co-occur with the Amphibolis and Posidonia spp

title: Effect of an exceptional rainfall event on the sea urchin (Paracentrotus lividus) stock and seagrass distribution in a Mediterranean coastal lagoon
all_species: cymodocea nodosa, zostera noltei, ruppia cirrhosa
notes: Data values from figure 4. Data obtained before and after the rainfall event.
driver effect: negative followed event and then recovery in less then 6 years
primary driver: Extreme rainfall event followed by flooding - reduce salinity, increase turbidity/siltation
statistical analysis: chi-squared test; visual - plot before and after rainfall event, inferential

title: Long-term changes of seagrass meadows in Botany Bay, Australia
all_species: posidonia australis, zostera capricorni, halophila ovalis, halophila decipiens
notes: Based on field surveys, it was assumed there was no change in seagrass coverage since the 1940s. The drivers are mentioned in the discussion and are not "ranked" as in there is not a primary driver listed.
primary driver: Dredging, release of sewage, pollutants, a change in sediments, oil spills, sea urchine grazing
tidied_drivers: coastal development (dredging, sewage, pollution, sedimentation, oil spills); sea urchin grazaing

title: Large-scale decline in offshore seagrass meadows in Bermuda
dom_species: thalassia testudinum, syringodium filiforme, halodule wrightii, halophila decipiens
all_species: thalassia testudinum, syringodium filiforme, halodule wrightii, halophila decipiens
notes: Data found in text in results section. The paper further splits into different areas but they don't do this for the whole site so I have gone with the total cover value. Say that they consider synergy of other drivers, but they don't really talk about it as an interaction of drivers.
primary driver: nutrients, physical damage by moorings, dredging, boat propellers, increased sedimentation
other drivers considered: low water temperatures with NAO, grazing,
tidied_drivers: nutrients; coastal development (dredging); sedimentation; boating (propeller, mooring)

Data from figure 9.

driver effect: varied by driver and by site
statistical analysis: correlation between the % cover of Z. noltii and each driver
